Francesc Muyas, PhD

11/07/2023

Clonal population structure in cancer genomes

A cancer ‘clone’ remains a loosely defined entity, and its purest definition is ‘a group of cells within the tumour that share a common ancestor’. However, is implies that any ancestor in the entire phylogenetic tree of a tumour can be identified as the founder (clone), even though it may show no biological difference from the rest of the cancer cells. This is why, in the field, we implicitly identify clones of interest, such as those that have growth/survival advantage.

In this lecture, we will explore the interpretation of the clonality of somatic mutations to gain insights into the clonal structure of cancer genomes.

We will use COLO829 mutations and other generated data, which can downloaded from https://github.com/cortes-ciriano-lab/CancerGenomicsCourse_EMBL-EBI.

In addition, we will mainly work with the R package Mobster.

Intersecting SNV coordinates with CNA coordinates

This step is required to map the copy number calls to the somatic SNVs. We need to know the total, major and minor copy number for each mutation.We can do this with the GenomicRanges R package.

#----
# Intersecting mutations with copy number calls
#----
# Intersecting copy number calls with individual mutations
VCF_bed <- with(All_muts, GRanges(CHROM, ranges=IRanges(POS-1, POS))) # Get the GRanges object from the VCF
CN_bed <- with(CN, GRanges(chromosome, ranges=IRanges(start, end), Total_CN = copyNumber, Major_CN = majorAlleleCopyNumber, Minor_CN = minorAlleleCopyNumber))

# Intersecting both bed files
o1 <- findOverlaps(VCF_bed,CN_bed)
HITS1 <- CN_bed[subjectHits(o1)]
DF1 <- VCF_bed[queryHits(o1)]
DF1 <- as.data.frame(DF1)
HITS2 <- as.data.frame(HITS1)
HITS2$CNA_coordinates <- paste(HITS2$seqnames,HITS2$start,HITS2$end, sep = '-')
DF2 <- cbind(DF1,HITS2)
DF2 <- DF2[,c('seqnames','end','CNA_coordinates','Total_CN','Major_CN','Minor_CN')]
colnames(DF2) <- c('CHROM','POS','CNA_coordinates','Total_CN','Major_CN','Minor_CN')
DF2 <- unique(DF2)

# Merge both files (VCF and CN)
All_muts2 <- merge(All_muts,DF2,by=c('CHROM','POS'),all.x = T)

# We only will analyse the autosomal chromosomes
# Sex chromosomes might have different ploidy levels, so we will ignore them for this analysis
All_muts2 <- All_muts2[All_muts2$CHROM %in% paste('chr',seq(1,22), sep = ''),]

# We already know the cancer purity of these samples
# As it is a cancer cell line (also calulated with copy number algorithms), it has a purity == 1
All_muts2$Purity <- 1

Calculate Cancer Cell Fraction (CCF)

The cancer cell fraction (CCF) is a measure that represents the proportion of cancer cells carrying a specific mutation within a tumour sample.

For this calculation, we need the copy number calls (previously loaded), the purity (previously estimated, = 1), and the VAFs (included in the mutation table). However, we still to calculate the multiplicity


Multiplicity calculation

The multiplicty represents the number of genomic segments harbouring each mutation.

This is the function:

# Multiplicity formula
ARGMIN_MULTIPLICITY <- function(VAF,mCN_T,MCN_T,TCN_T,TCN_N,purity){
  
  if (MCN_T > 0){
    MULTIPLICITY <- arg.min(seq(1,MCN_T,1), function(x) abs(VAF*(1/(purity*x))*(purity*TCN_T+(1-purity)*TCN_N) - 1))
    return(MULTIPLICITY)
  } else {
    return (NA)
  }
  
}


Now we apply this formula to all our mutations:

# Multiplicity calculation
# A little bit of description
All_muts2$Multiplicity <- apply(All_muts2, 1, function(x) ARGMIN_MULTIPLICITY(VAF = as.numeric(x['T_VAF']),
                                                                    mCN_T = as.numeric(x['Minor_CN']),
                                                                    MCN_T = as.numeric(x['Major_CN']),
                                                                    TCN_T = as.numeric(x['Total_CN']),
                                                                    TCN_N = 2,
                                                                    purity = 1))

Cancer cell fraction calculation

This function will calculate the CCF:

# Cancer Cell fraction calculation
CCF_calc <- function(VAF,Multiplicity,TCN_T,purity){
  if (TCN_T > 0){
    ccf <- VAF / (Multiplicity * purity) * (purity * TCN_T + 2*(1-purity))
    return(ccf)
  } else{
    return (NA)
  }
}

Once we have the multiplicity and the formula, we can calculate the CCF :

# Cancer Cell fraction Calculation
All_muts2$CCF <- apply(All_muts2, 1, function(x) CCF_calc(VAF = as.numeric(x['T_VAF']),
                                                Multiplicity = as.numeric(x['Multiplicity']),
                                                TCN_T = as.numeric(x['Total_CN']),
                                                purity = 1))

Let’s take a look to the CCF estimations:

ggplot(All_muts2[All_muts2$sampleID == 'COLO829.2',], aes(x = CCF))+
  geom_density() +
  facet_grid(.~sampleID) +
  theme_bw()


Important We have by far too many mutations for a fast and example computation of the CCF. For this reason, we do a random sampling of mutations:

set.seed(1111)
All_muts2 <- All_muts2[sample(nrow(All_muts2), 15000), ]

Inferring clones using Mobster

Clonal reconstruction from bulk sequencing data involves complex computational algorithms and statistical models. Today, we will use Mobster. Mobster is a package that implements a model-based approach for subclonal deconvolution of cancer genome sequencing data (Caravagna et al; PMID: 32879509).

1. Inferring clones in the original COLO829T sample

Since CCF values usually peak at around 1.0 for clonal mutations (i.e., present in 100% of the input cells), this tool suggests to adjust standard CCF estimates dividing them by 2 in order to reflect the peak of an heterozygous clonal mutation at 50% VAF for a 100% pure bulk sample. The results VAFs cannot be grater than 1.

set.seed(1111)
All_muts3 <- All_muts2[All_muts2$sampleID == 'COLO829T',]
All_muts3$VAF <- All_muts3$CCF/2
All_muts3 <- All_muts3[All_muts3$VAF < 1,]

hist(All_muts3$VAF, breaks = 100)


Fitting clones

Now, we can use the function mobster_fit to fit the clones here:

fit1 = mobster_fit(
  All_muts3, 
  K = 1:3,
  samples = 10,
  init = 'random',
  maxIter = 100,
  seed = 1111,
  N_cutoff = 50)

Let’s check the results of the best fit:

best_fit1 <- fit1$best
plot(best_fit1)
